eatures:**\n- Developers can define automation logic using natural language instead of YAML\n- Code is open-source under MIT license\n- AI agents have read-only permissions by default\n- Write operations require authorization through a \"safe-outputs\" mechanism to prevent malicious code injection\n\n### 2. Multiple AI Agent Integration (February 5, 2026)\nGitHub announced the integration of multiple programming AI agents into the platform:\n- **Anthropic's Claude**\n- **OpenAI's Codex**\n\nThis feature is available to **Copilot Pro Plus and Enterprise subscribers** across:\n- Web interface\n- Mobile apps\n- VS Code\n\nThis is part of GitHub's \"Agent HQ\" (智能体总部) strategy, allowing developers to:\n- Switch between different AI agents for task creation, issue handling, and pull requests\n- Evaluate code generation effectiveness across different AI models\n- GitHub plans to integrate additional AI agents from Google, Cognition, and xAI\n\n## Industry Context\n\nThe search results indicate that by February 2026:\n- AI agents have evolved from simple code completion tools to autonomous workflow participants\n- Projects deeply integrated with AI Agents see development cycles shortened by nearly 60%\n- AI agents can now autonomously run tests in containers, compare thousands of historical commits, and locate problematic logic within 30 seconds\n- The focus has shifted from \"code completion\" to \"autonomous project management\" capabilities\n\nWould you like me to search for more specific information about any of these releases?\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."
